We’re pleased to announce that we now have these absolutely mint cinemodded MAMIYA 645 Sekor-C lenses in PL mount with 95mm fronts ready for your (and our) next project.

These are not the newer ‘N’ versions but the original ‘C’ versions which have less coating. They have a wonderful ‘IMAX’ type rendering that you can’t quite describe but you can certainly feel and they’ll flare tastefully while lifting shadows with really any light source. Even ambient. 

In our opinion they’ll intercut with Leica Rs and they may even be a better or more affordable option for your next project. 

The 80mm f1.9 is a gem, the 110mm f2.8 could find its way into any project, and the 35, 45, and 55 really do have that special Mamiya magic.

From special flares to hard stops, smooth throws and an X factor, these may very well become our next favorite lens set!

This set includes the Sekor C:
35mm f3.5
45mm f2.8
55mm f2.8
80mm f1.9
110mm f2.8

ps - they’re some of the most well built lenses out there and cover Alexa 65.

You’re going to see a lot more of this very special lens in the days to come as it may very well become one of our new favorites. We’ve been eyeing this beast for years. 

Made from 1995-2006, the Leica R 70-180mm f2.8 Vario-APO-Elmarit was and still is at the top of its class blowing other zooms and even most primes out of the water with its stunning image quality and delicate Leica characteristics. About 2,250 lenses were made which makes finding great copies of this gem very tough. 

It’s hefty and of course solidly built, has a built in collar with a female 1/4-20, ultra smooth Leica R mechanics, and a 300 degree focus throw from the factory!

Ours is fully modded by @ducloslenses which means it passes the test, comes in Canon EF mount, comes equipped with a declicked iris, focus and zoom gears, and a 77mm/80mm OD front ring. 

We have the matching Leica R 21-35mm f3.5 aspherical and plenty of other R primes to pair with this workhorse of a lens.

Have any questions about this lens or any other lenses we have in inventory? Comment below and we’ll make sure to answer. Happy shooting!

For so many of us, photography or filmmaking started out as a hobby. The excitement of the new and unknown, pure fun, and creativity motivated by nothing but our inner artist were emotions we used to experience regularly. If that same hobby turned into a job or your career over the years, chances are you’ve experienced burnout or have lost that original spark or sense of adventure you once had. ‘Permission to Be Yourself’ is a film that hopefully inspires and helps its viewers get back to their roots of simply doing this all for fun.

I’ve been messing with film again recently. I’ve gone in and out of the process over the years for different reasons. The last time I ditched film it was because I couldn’t wait for the results and wanted instant gratification. Today, I find myself wanting less screens, phones, presets, and exports and wanting to be more present in a moment. Yes, shooting film may slow you down, but for me the process is deeper than that. Removing the EVF and screen on the back of the camera is more immersive to me. I’m also constantly hungry to learn and strengthen my eyes for what makes film so special and really like shooting it alongside digital stills and motion for reference. 

I’ll probably be into it for a while, then back off, then back in again. We’ll see. For now, I’m in.

A few months back we had a really cool project that involved a top-down shot of an elegant table being set inside a dining room. We needed a way to connect the table to the property we were shooting on and in pre-production we thought, “what if we could cut to that same table outside at the very end of the piece?” Everyone loved the idea and we went with it. 
We utilized a tool I like to often in SmalHD monitors which is the ‘Image Capture’ and ‘Image Overlay’ tools which allowed us to perfectly match the set table from inside to the set table from outside. We overlaid the set table from inside at 50% opacity and then set the table outside while viewing the SmallHD Cine24. It took about 5 minutes for 4 of us to put it all together and we had a lot of fun doing so. 
Next time you need to match a shot, use SmallHD Image Capture and Overlay tools. 🫡✅👍🏽🖥️🎥
